{"title":"GRIP: A General Robotic Incremental Potential Contact Simulation Dataset for Unified Deformable-Rigid Coupled Grasping","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Accurate, scalable simulation of coupled soft–rigid grasping with robust frictional contact is challenging: IPC is precise but traditionally too slow and fragile for large-scale, multi-environment data generation.","method":"They develop a GPU-parallel, multi-environment IPC simulator that preserves IPC’s intersection- and inversion-free frictional contact while scaling efficiently. Key design choices include environment isolation during collision detection and step-size filtering so each environment advances with its own step size, per-environment convergence tracking to freeze finished environments, failure detection to isolate bad runs, and parallel linear solves. Run in FP64, the system achieves strong scalability on an H100 GPU, e.g., ~40× speedup for UMI grippers with 400 environments and ~16× for LEAP Hands with 512 environments, enabling large-scale grasp validation."},{"problem":"Existing grasp datasets largely omit soft grippers and deformable manipulands and often rely on simulators that permit penetrations, limiting data quality and model generalization.","method":"GRIP is a fully automated pipeline that generates and validates 100K grasp poses over 1,200 objects with both soft UMI grippers and rigid LEAP Hands. Soft fingers are tetrahedralized (TetWild) with real-world material/friction parameters; objects are watertight/tetrahedralized with domain-randomized properties. Candidate grasps are synthesized via GPD (UMI) and DexGraspNet adapted to LEAP with an added normal-alignment energy; inverse kinematics adjusts fingertips along object normals to meet IPC’s contact threshold (d̂=1e−3 m), discarding remaining penetrations; bimanual grasps are composed by clustering/pairing unimanual candidates and filtering with an approximate force-closure metric. Validation applies six axis-aligned gravity perturbations under IPC contact; resulting grasps have zero penetration (D1=0) and tight clearance (D2≈0.12 cm), and training UGG on GRIP outperforms Isaac Gym–filtered data (success 26.3% vs 7.9% on full set; 31.6% vs 17.5% on bottles)."},{"problem":"Predicting contact-induced stress in deformable objects during grasping is important to avoid damage, but labeled stress fields across diverse grasps are scarce.","method":"Using GRIP’s per-trajectory stress annotations, they train a stress-prediction network that inputs the object point cloud and gripper mesh at a grasp pose. The model follows a GNN backbone with a cross-attention module to encode hand–object interactions and outputs pointwise von Mises stress. On mugs and bowls with leave-object-out testing (~200–250 grasps/object), it achieves 7–9% Relative MAE and KL divergence <0.2, and real-to-sim experiments show qualitative agreement between predicted and simulated stress distributions."}]}
